  // ═══ AQA GCSE 2025 entries + remaining 0v topics ══════════════════════
  "germany-2025-0-0": { summary: "Q01 — How does Interpretation B differ from Interpretation A about why Germans supported the Nazi Party? [4m]", topic: "Why Germans supported the Nazis — how interpretations differ [4m]", markScheme: "CONFIRMED May 2025 (Docsity). L2 (3-4m): Developed analysis explains how Int A and Int B differ about reasons for Nazi support. One may emphasise genuine belief/enthusiasm (ideology, promise of strong leadership, nationalism), while the other emphasises opportunism or propaganda. Must cite specific content from both interpretations." },
  "germany-2025-1-0": { summary: "Q02 — Why might the authors of Interpretations A and B have a different interpretation about why Germans supported the Nazi Party? [4m]", topic: "Why Germans supported the Nazis — why interpretations differ [4m]", markScheme: "CONFIRMED May 2025 (Docsity). L2 (3-4m): Analyses provenance of each interpretation to explain different viewpoints. Consider: when written (contemporary vs retrospective), who wrote it (German/non-German; Nazi supporter vs critic), their purpose and audience, their access to information. Use contextual knowledge of Nazi propaganda, economic recovery after 1933, depression conditions." },
  "germany-2025-2-0": { summary: "Q03 — Which interpretation gives the more convincing opinion about why Germans supported the Nazi Party? [8m]", topic: "Why Germans supported the Nazis — which more convincing [8m]", markScheme: "CONFIRMED May 2025 (Docsity). L4 (7-8m): Sustained evaluation of BOTH interpretations using contextual knowledge. Nazi support: genuine ideological appeal (nationalism, anti-Communism, promise of order); economic recovery 1933-38 (unemployment fell from 6m to <1m); Hitler’s charisma and Goebbels’ propaganda; Volksgemeinschaft (people’s community) sense of belonging. But: conformity not always genuine enthusiasm; fear of Gestapo reprisals; Jews, Communists, church groups who did NOT support. Must evaluate which interpretation is MORE convincing with specific evidence." },
  "germany-2025-3-0": { summary: "Q04 — Describe two problems faced by Kaiser Wilhelm II in ruling Germany before 1914. [4m]", topic: "Describe two problems faced by Kaiser Wilhelm II before 1914", markScheme: "CONFIRMED May 2025 (Docsity). 4m AO1. Problems: growing SPD (Social Democrat) opposition (largest party in Reichstag by 1912; challenged conservative ruling class); Reichstag blocked some reform bills (Kaiser could not always get legislation passed); nationalist pressure groups demanded aggressive foreign policy; industrial unrest and strikes; Alsace-Lorraine resentment; tension with Austria-Hungary and Russia in Balkans. 1m per problem + 1m per supporting detail." },
  "germany-2025-4-0": { summary: "Q05 — In what ways did Nazi racial policies affect the lives of people in Germany before 1939? Explain your answer. [8m]", topic: "Nazi racial policies affect lives in Germany before 1939 [8m]", markScheme: "CONFIRMED May 2025 (Docsity). 8m AO2. L3 (7-8m): Developed explanation of multiple impacts — Jews: Nuremberg Laws 1935 (loss of citizenship; marriage bans); Kristallnacht Nov 1938 (synagogues destroyed; c.30,000 Jews arrested; Jewish businesses attacked); economic exclusion (boycotts April 1933; ‘Aryanisation’ of businesses); expulsion from professions. Non-Aryan groups: Romani, Black Germans, people with disabilities (T4 euthanasia programme precursors; forced sterilisation). Impact varied in severity over time (escalating persecution). Must show HOW racial policies affected daily life, not just list them." },
  "germany-2025-5-0": { summary: "Q06 — Which was the more important reason for the Nazis’ ability to control Germany: Nazi terror or Nazi culture and censorship? Explain with reference to both bullet points. [12m]", topic: "Nazi control — terror vs culture/censorship [12m]", markScheme: "CONFIRMED May 2025 (Docsity). 12m. Nazi terror: SS (Himmler) and Gestapo (Heydrich); arrest without trial; concentration camps (Dachau 1933+); Night of the Long Knives 1934; block wardens informing on neighbours; People’s Courts; chilling effect creating self-censorship. Nazi culture/censorship: Goebbels’ Ministry of Propaganda (1933); control of radio (70% German homes had a set by 1939); Volksempfänger (people’s receiver); book burnings 1933; Reich Chamber of Culture (artists/writers required to join); Leni Riefenstahl films; Nuremberg rallies. L4: evaluates BOTH, considers how they complemented each other (propaganda persuaded; terror silenced resisters), reaches clear overall judgement on which was MORE important." },
  "america1920-2025-0-0": { summary: "Q01 — How does Interpretation B differ from Interpretation A about the significance of the civil rights movement in the 1960s? [4m]", topic: "the significance of the civil rights movement in the 1960s — inte", markScheme: "L2 (3-4m): Developed analysis of interpretations explains differences with specific content from each. L1 (1-2m): Simple identification." },
  "america1920-2025-1-0": { summary: "Q02 — Why might the authors differ in their interpretation about the significance of the civil rights movement in the 1960s? [4m]", topic: "the significance of the civil rights movement in the 1960s — why ", markScheme: "L2 (3-4m): Developed provenance analysis (time written, author perspective/experience/purpose) with contextual knowledge. L1 (1-2m): Simple provenance point." },
  "america1920-2025-2-0": { summary: "Q03 — Which interpretation gives the more convincing opinion about the significance of the civil rights movement in the 1960s? [8m]", topic: "the significance of the civil rights movement in the 1960s — whic", markScheme: "L4 (7-8m): Complex evaluation of BOTH interpretations with sustained contextual knowledge — evaluates relationship between them. L3 (5-6m): Developed evaluation of both. L2 (3-4m): Simple evaluation of one." },
  "america1920-2025-3-0": { summary: "Describe two features of McCarthyism in the USA in the early 1950s [4m]", topic: "Describe two features of McCarthyism in the USA in the early 1950", markScheme: "4m AO1: 1m per feature + 1m per supporting detail. Two distinct features required." },
  "america1920-2025-4-0": { summary: "In what ways did life change for Black Americans in the years 1945–1965? [8m]", topic: "In what ways did life change for Black Americans in the years 194", markScheme: "L3 (7-8m): Developed explanation of multiple ways with causal links. L2 (5-6m): One well-developed way. L1 (1-4m): Simple statements." },
  "america1920-2025-5-0": { summary: "Which was the more important reason for the fall of Richard Nixon: the Watergate scandal or the impact of the Vietnam War on his presidency? [12m]", topic: "Which was the more important reason for the fall of Richard Nixon", markScheme: "L4 (10-12m): Balanced argument with specific evidence for BOTH bullet points, clear overall judgement. L3 (7-9m): Addresses both but unbalanced. L2 (4-6m): One bullet only." },
  "russia1894-2025-0-0": { summary: "Q01 — How does Interpretation B differ from Interpretation A about the significance of Stalin’s economic policies? [4m]", topic: "the significance of Stalin’s economic policies — interpretations ", markScheme: "L2 (3-4m): Developed analysis of interpretations explains differences with specific content from each. L1 (1-2m): Simple identification." },
