  "peopleshealth-2024-3-0": { summary: "Q2 — Write a clear and organised summary that analyses air quality since 1900. Support your summary with examples. [9m]", topic: "Write a clear and organised summary that analyses air quality sin", markScheme: "L4 (8-9m): Clear, organised summary with analytical focus — explains how/why the development evolved across the period; uses multiple well-chosen examples integrated into the analysis. L3 (5-7m): Organised summary with examples but less analytical. L2 (3-4m): Partly organised summary with some examples. L1 (1-2m): Isolated points without structure." },
  "peopleshealth-2024-4-0": { summary: "Q3 — Why did public health improve in the second half of the 1800s? Explain your answer. [10m]", topic: "Why did public health improve in the second half of the 1800s? Ex", markScheme: "CONFIRMED QP Jun24. L4: mid-19th century public health improved due to: John Snow’s cholera investigation 1854 (showed contaminated water caused disease); Bazalgette’s London sewers 1858-75 (eliminated cholera); 1875 Public Health Act (compulsory sewers/clean water for all towns); germ theory (Pasteur 1861, Koch identified specific bacteria) giving scientific basis for reform; Edwin Chadwick’s 1842 Report showing link between poverty and disease. Multiple causes linked to each other (e.g., germ theory gave government scientific justification to act). L4 requires both multiple causes AND causal linkage." },
  "peopleshealth-2024-5-0": { summary: "Q4 — \"The authorities in towns and monasteries in medieval Britain (1250–1500) cared very little about public health.\" How far do you agree? [18m]", topic: "\"The authorities in towns and monasteries in medieval Britain (12", markScheme: "CONFIRMED QP Jun24. L4: For ‘cared very little’: monasteries did provide infirmaries but mainly for their own monks; towns had few public health regulations; Black Death (1348) inadequately understood (miasma theory); population growth caused squalor. Against: monasteries did build fish ponds, piped water, drainage; guilds regulated food quality in some towns; some town authorities tried to enforce street cleaning; wealthy individuals funded hospitals like St Bartholomew’s. L4: sustained argument considering both evidence for and against, reaching a substantiated overall judgement about ‘how far’." },
  "peopleshealth-2024-5-1": { summary: "Q5 — \"The most important factor in improving public health in Britain was government action.\" How far do you agree? [18m]", topic: "\"The most important factor in improving public health in Britain ", markScheme: "CONFIRMED QP Jun24. L4: For ‘cared very little’: monasteries did provide infirmaries but mainly for their own monks; towns had few public health regulations; Black Death (1348) inadequately understood (miasma theory); population growth caused squalor. Against: monasteries did build fish ponds, piped water, drainage; guilds regulated food quality in some towns; some town authorities tried to enforce street cleaning; wealthy individuals funded hospitals like St Bartholomew’s. L4: sustained argument considering both evidence for and against, reaching a substantiated overall judgement about ‘how far’." },
