  // Edexcel 1HIA/10 — Crime & Punishment in Britain & Whitechapel, Summer 2022 (P68664A)
  "crimepunishment-2022-0-0": { summary: "Two features of the work of H Division in the policing of Whitechapel", topic: "Whitechapel: policing Whitechapel",
    markScheme: "1 mark per feature + 1 for supporting detail (max 4, AO1). E.g. H Division officers walked a beat (patrolling streets to prevent crime, also managing drunks, traffic, accidents); 15 CID detectives assigned (using investigative techniques); or H Division involvement in trying to catch Jack the Ripper (Inspector Abberline led the investigation)." },
  "crimepunishment-2022-1-0": { summary: "Usefulness of two sources for an enquiry into workhouses in Whitechapel", topic: "Whitechapel: living & working conditions",
    markScheme: "L1–3, AO3. Source A (Jack London’s account from his book about conditions in a workhouse casual ward): useful for daily routine and punitive food provision; London spent time with others who had experience of these conditions, though he was writing to attract public attention to harsh conditions. Source B (newspaper drawing of a queue of people entering a workhouse, titled to draw attention to the poor): shows overcrowding and despair; newspaper illustration intended to attract readers, but drawn after the visit and may be dramatised." },
  "crimepunishment-2022-2-0": { summary: "Follow-up enquiry from Source A into workhouses in Whitechapel", topic: "Whitechapel: living & working conditions",
    markScheme: "1 mark each for: detail from Source A (e.g. ‘I would be given bread and skilly’), linked question (e.g. why was food in a workhouse so basic?), source type (e.g. workhouse financial accounts), and how it helps (e.g. showing how much money was available per inmate and why food was so basic)." },
  "crimepunishment-2022-3-0": { summary: "One way attitudes to poaching in the medieval period were similar to attitudes c1700–c1900", topic: "Crime in medieval & Anglo-Saxon England, c1000–1500",
    markScheme: "L1 (1–2) / L2 (3–4), AO1:2/AO2:2. E.g. in both periods poaching was seen by many as a social crime that didn’t harm anyone (medieval: common land reserved for the king; c1700–1900: landlords seen as selfish); or in both periods poaching challenged authority (Forest Laws in the medieval period; Black Acts c1700–1900)." },
